# 1️⃣ What are **Epochs**?

**Answer**

An **epoch** means one complete pass of the entire training dataset through the model during training.

For example, if the dataset has **1000 images**, one epoch means the model has seen **all 1000 images once**.

We usually train the model for **multiple epochs** so that it can gradually learn better patterns from the data.

---

### Example

If you train for **10 epochs**, the model will go through the **entire dataset 10 times**.

---

# 2️⃣ What are **Resampling Techniques**?

Resampling techniques are used when the **dataset is imbalanced** (for example, more normal images than disease images).

They help balance the dataset so the model does not become biased.

---

### Common Resampling Techniques

**1️⃣ Oversampling**

Increase the number of samples in the **minority class**.

Example: Duplicate or generate more disease images.

---

**2️⃣ Undersampling**

Reduce the number of samples in the **majority class**.

Example: Remove some normal images.

---

**3️⃣ SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique)**

Generate **synthetic samples** of the minority class instead of simply duplicating them.

---

### Simple interview line

> Resampling techniques such as **oversampling and undersampling** are used to balance imbalanced datasets so the 
model does not bias toward the majority class.

